tributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book chronicles and explains the role of suburbs in North American cities since the mid-twentieth century. Examining fifteen case studies from New York to Vancouver, Atlanta to Chicago, Montreal to Phoenix, The Life of North American Suburbs traces the insightful connection between the evolution of suburbs and the cultural dynamics of modern society. Suburbs are uniquely significant spaces: their creation and evolution reflect the shifting demographics, race relations, modes of production, cultural fabric, and class structures of society at large. The case studies investigate the place of suburbs within their wider metropolitan constellations: the crucial role they play in the cultural, economic, political, and spatial organization of the city. Together, the chapters paint a compelling portrait of North American cities and their dynamic suburban landscapes.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aCities and townszNorth AmericaxGrowth. 0aSuburbszNorth America. 0aUrbanizationzNorth America. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Comparative Politics.2bisacsh  aCanada.  aCities.  aComparative urbanism.  aMontreal.  aNew York City.  aSuburbanization.  aSuburbs.  aUnited States.  aUrban.  aurban geography.  aurban history.1 aAndrew, Caroline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrunelle, Derek, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClery, Tom, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDefilippis, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFranovic, Angela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGilbert, Liette, econtributor.4ctb4https